at engagement is a novel hypothesis about God that embraces legitimate criticisms of both process theology (Cobb) and ground-of-being theology (Neville) while integrating insights from both ways of thinking. God's transcendence and immanence, indeterminacy and determinacy are fully affirmed. The entire argument serves as an example of why a fallible and pluralistic form of theology, one that embraces and learns from difference instead of trying to eliminate it, is important for the future of theology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aGod (Christianity)xHistory of doctrinesy21st century. 0aPhilosophical theologyxHistoryy21st century. 0aProcess theology. 4aPhilosophy : Epistemology. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Religion. 4aPhilosophy : Process Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Theology. 7aRELIGION / Theology.2bisacsh1 aPeirce, Charles S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPragmatism, American, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2022z978311149185140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848721240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438487212423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438487212/original  a978-3-11-149185-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles